TUnit uses `[Before(...)]` and `[After(...)]` attributes with a scope enum, plus class lifecycle hooks. Here's a sketch for each scope:

## 1. Before/After Every Test (method-level)

```csharp
public class DatabaseTests
{
    [Before(Test)]
    public void ResetDatabase()
    {
        // Runs before each [Test] in this class
        InMemoryDb.Reset();
    }

    [After(Test)]
    public void Cleanup()
    {
        // Runs after each [Test] in this class
    }

    [Test]
    public async Task QueryReturnsExpectedRow() { /* ... */ }
}
```

## 2. Once Per Class (class-level fixture)

```csharp
public class ServiceIntegrationTests : IAsyncInitializer, IAsyncDisposable
{
    private NpgsqlConnection _connection = null!;

    // Runs once before the first test in this class
    public async Task InitializeAsync()
    {
        _connection = new NpgsqlConnection("...");
        await _connection.OpenAsync();
    }

    // Runs once after the last test in this class
    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await _connection.DisposeAsync();
    }

    [Test]
    public async Task InsertWorks() { /* use _connection */ }
}
```

Or with attributes on static methods:

```csharp
public class ServiceTests
{
    [Before(Class)]
    public static async Task SetUp(ClassHookContext context)
    {
        // Once before first test in the class
    }

    [After(Class)]
    public static async Task TearDown(ClassHookContext context)
    {
        // Once after last test in the class
    }
}
```

## 3. Once Per Assembly

```csharp
public class GlobalWireMockSetup
{
    [Before(Assembly)]
    public static async Task StartWireMock(AssemblyHookContext context)
    {
        WireMockServer.Start();
    }

    [After(Assembly)]
    public static async Task StopWireMock(AssemblyHookContext context)
    {
        WireMockServer.Stop();
    }
}
```

The class can live anywhere in the assembly — TUnit discovers it automatically.

## 4. Once Per Entire Test Session (global)

```csharp
public class GlobalDatabaseMigration
{
    [Before(TestSession)]
    public static async Task ApplyMigrations(TestSessionContext context)
    {
        await MigrationRunner.MigrateAsync();
    }

    [After(TestSession)]
    public static async Task DropDatabase(TestSessionContext context)
    {
        await MigrationRunner.TearDownAsync();
    }
}
```

---

**Summary table:**

| Scope | Attribute | Method must be | Context parameter |
|-------|-----------|----------------|-------------------|
| Each test | `[Before(Test)]` / `[After(Test)]` | Instance | _(none required)_ |
| Class | `[Before(Class)]` / `[After(Class)]` | `static` | `ClassHookContext` |
| Assembly | `[Before(Assembly)]` / `[After(Assembly)]` | `static` | `AssemblyHookContext` |
| Session | `[Before(TestSession)]` / `[After(TestSession)]` | `static` | `TestSessionContext` |

Key points:
- **Test-level** hooks are instance methods on the test class itself.
- **Class and above** hooks must be `static` and can live in any class in the assembly.
- For class-scoped resource lifetime, implementing `IAsyncInitializer` / `IAsyncDisposable` on the test class is often the cleanest option.
